I made modular bracelet system - just for fun and to learn new techniques. 
How to make it - for a simple bracelet - print complete chain with proper lenght, connector and pin. Every extra part measures 1cm.
Edit2921016: Sorry people, complete chains were not ended with proper part, Im replacing these with right ones. For those who have printed it from original file I'm adding new connector (connectorREP.stl) what will fit. Also repaired pin (pin_2.stl) was added.

There are five main components of this system:
-first fraction, optimized for connecting with last part connector. It has no integrated axis so you can easily swap it if it breaks or you need extending. You will need extra pin.
-second is spare part used for extending bracelet. You will need extra pin.
-third part is main part of chain, use it if you want connected chain already from printer. It is loose enough, so you wont have to clean it up.
-fourth part is end connector, optimized for connection with first part. It has no integrated axis so you can easily swap it if it breaks or you need extending. You will need extra pin.
-lastly fifth part is pin used for connecting modules.
if you have any suggestions how to connect ends more effectively - let me know. Thanks

title: The "Revolver"... easy to print but challenging to solve!
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text: The "Revolver" is a 3D printed puzzle with 41 independent moving parts that revolve / slide around a two part Retainer. The prints are all easy and straight forward and the result is really impressive... This is similar to a Rubik's cube in that the aim is to align / group matching colours but there are two puzzles in one with the Revolver as you can align rows or columns to be the same colours. A single / dual; colour version is also available as a separate thing for people wanting this puzzle but without six filament colours available. This alternative has six indented shapes to align instead of colours. Files available at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1347886 One space is left to allow for the Sliders to move one space at a time. This means you need to plan your moves as you move towards your goal... of course you can pull it apart if you get frustrated with it and realign it that way but if you're really up for the challenge glue the thread so it will never come apart! The parts are all easy prints and assemble is very straight forward. However, you will need at least 6 colours of filament. The images provided creates a great result. Black is used for the Retainer. All Revolvers are printed in White and colours used for the Sliders are White, Red, Yellow, Blue, Orange and Green. As you need to leave one Slider out to make a space for movement make all the Revolvers the same colour as the Slider that you decide to leave out. The reason being, you will see the underlying Revolver colour in the empty space so the gap is hardly noticeable. The space effectively becomes a block of the Revolvers colour (Refer to images for additional information). To achieve the end result does take time but it's well worth the effort. You need at least 6 colours of filament and to change the filament between prints. Most machines capable of printing fine detail and good slicing apps should have no problem with the fine tolerances in this print. Watching it come together is satisfying... once it's together, and with the Slider colours well messed up, it can be very frustrating... until you solve it and then it's very satisfying again! Print the puzzle... then can you do it? And, if you do... post images of your success! Please refer to the print instructions and images for additional information. Note: If you like this check out all my other fun and practical designs.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.20mm / Standard

Infill:

3 Shells / 35% Infill

Notes: Easy prints however the 'Retainer' file needs to be printed with 3 shells / 35% infill to ensure it is strong enough when screwed together. The other parts (Revolvers and Sliders) can be printed with 2 Shells / 20% infill as they don't need to be as strong. Note: Most accurate machines / good slicing apps should have no problems with these files however the tolerances are fine so other less accurate machines may not slide / rotate as easily or screw together easily. This has been tested on a Replicator 2 and 5th Generation Replicator with great results.

Assembly required... Remove the Raft then assemble the Sliders into the Revolvers. Make sure they all move freely / smoothly as the Sliders need to be able to move from Revolver to Revolver to solve the puzzle. One Revolver needs to be left with only 5 of 6 spaces filled (i.e. leave one out) as a space is required to allow you to move the sliders around one space at a time. This is what makes it challenging... like a Rubik's cube but round with rotating / sliding parts. Once the Revolvers / Sliders are assembled carefully place them onto the long part of the retainer. Once all are in place screw the second part of the Retainer (with the thread protruding) into the assembled Retainer / Revolvers / Sliders.. You only need to make it finger tight as you may need to unscrew it later if you can't solve it... although try not to cheat! You can glue the thread so it will never come undone if you are up for the challenge... Please refer to the images provided for additional information. QUICK TIP: As you need to leave one Slider out to make a space for movement make all the Revolvers the same colour as the Slider that is 'missing'. The reason being, you will see the underlying Revolver colour in the empty space so the gap is hardly noticeable.

This is the text for the one ring from The Lord of the Rings. Follow the post-printing instructions to make a ring with text that is normally invisible but glows when exposed to UV light. (The one in the books used fire, but I don't have a volcano... or magic. This one just melts and burns in fire.) You'll also need polycaprolactone (PCL) for this build. PCL is available in pellet form from several online stores. I get mine from MCM Elextronics under the brand Polymold. Notes: Use glow in the dark filament.

Heat water to boiling (or just below).
Pour enough PCL pellets to make your ring into the hot water.
When the PCL is clear fish it out of the water with a metal utensil (like a spoon or fork). PCL is not-toxic and food safe (unless yours says otherwise). The PCL will be cool enough to work with your hands,but watch out for pockets of hot water trapped inside.
Fill the space between the outer ring and your finger with molten PCL. Don't cover the outer layer of glow in the dark plastic because you'll need to cut it off. You may need to put the ring in the hot water to keep the PCL moldable.
Shape the edges of the ring and remove any excess PCL. The excess can be re-melted and used for other projects.
Let the ring cool. For faster cooling run cold (or at least cool) water over it.
Remove the outer layer of glowing plastic. I'm sure there's a better way, but I used a pocket knife, and file. (This is the most difficult part of the build.)
Touch up the ring as needed with short dips in hot water and you're done.

Don't Over Think It So I was trying to copy old scroll images on the web and wondering how to import images and trace the outline, when I realized all I needed to do was to sketch a line then extrude it. So I drew a line in the shape of a scroll from the side perspective and extruded it. I added text which was moved and rotated into postion and then using polyline, drew a crooked line down the middle. Then using the split object command, I used the crooked line as the splitting entity and wha-la, there it was. I added loops (torus split in half) regrouped the text and combined. By exporting each half as a selection to Meshmixer and auto-repairing, the prints came out fine the first time. I did scale down by 50%, flipped one "side" and printed both "halves" at the same time. Note: I needed to ungroup the text and regroup the text to combine with the scroll body and loops on each side of the line. (separation -> sepa & ration)

This is my version of the 16014 bearing used in the Ciclop scanner.
It's not as tough as the commercial 16014 which has a radial load rating of at least 2 tons, but may serve the purpose for those of you scanning less weighty objects.
It comprises three printed parts and eight 9.5mm steel ball bearings.
The ball bearings are inexpensive and widely available. (in the UK)
To assemble it you will need a flat surface to work on, a small screwdriver or similar object to manipulate the ball bearings and common sense about health and safety.
You can either guess how to assemble it or read the instructions. That's entirely up to you.
NOTE: Rotate the cage through 180° before printing (i.e. flat side down)

description.text: Still putting my Ormerod 1 kit together - it's rather like the Curates egg - good in parts. There are some very nicely designed parts, but the original Y-Axis belt Clamping method can best be described as TOTAL GARBAGE - I tried several times to get enough tension & just gave up. I tried iamburnys RepRap_Pro_Ormerod_iamburnys_Y-axis_BeltClamp-_Parametric, ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:263720 ) but the belt kept slipping out, so I added an extra screw & some nut holders to really really clamp it in tightly -combined with a Y-idler tensioner ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:356130 ) there is no slipping now, and the tension is very easily adjusted :-) I'm also not too impressed with the kludgy white targets needed for leveling, a printer without Marlin style Auto levelling with bed warp compensation is, IMHO, a nearly useless time waster - it's next to fix on my list. As an example, my Solidoodle 2 was a nightmare to use before I added a $10 Inductive sensor (from learCNC) and FlashForge Build Tape. Now it's a joy to use - just load a STL and print, no levelling needed anymore - I just need to setup the Z height once.

Notes: done entirely in PLA
No raft, as my bed is pretty much spot-on level with extruder and a raft will effect the finished surface of the upper and lower plate if used (though with careful after-print work you can usually counter it)
No support, I generally never use support in my designs, partly for the same reason I don't use rafts (it effects finished surface) and partly because I hate picking the crap off my prints when I'm to impatient to wait to use them lol, the only exception to the rule is on the two middle box sections that span the centre spar, support is needed for the print over the spars width.
Ive recently ran a print of one of the centre sections in ABS just to test and found the end result acceptable, If however you do choose to print entirely with PLA as Ive done don't be tempted to increase Infill levels to greatly in an attempt to increase your prints ruggedness as you'll find it has a completely opposite effect with PLA in this case and the increased stiffness of the print will only serve to increase brittleness. .... not exactly ideal qualities if like myself you don't always make the most.....erm..... "gentle" landings

Pandora's box 500mm quadcopter named as such because as soon as I began printing it out and assembling I knew It'd likely be a nightmare situation if I opened this "box" again....hence "Pandora's box" lol as it turned out it was a very simple operation to build and only needed some minor changes in the original print designs to get the desired end products. printed in layered platform level design to facilitate print time, ease of build, ease of repair/replacement and allow configuration to desired needs (add/remove a platform layer as more or less space is required for electronics. lower two layers are entirely optional as these are used to incase the batteries, I'm a bit of a stickler when it comes to nice clean crisp lines and have never liked strapping my batteries to the outside of my quads. Frame spars are made from 15x15 square carbon fibre tube (available from HobbyKing for under a tenner), Motor mounts were taken from an old frame I had knocking about but any mount could be used.

For years I wanted to print a spintop. But with the geared motor extruders this was not possible because the pointed tip while being printed would accumulate too much heat and melt away. With a geared motor you can't control the exact amount of extruded material which is just what you need to do when you want to slow down in the upper layers to give the plastic more time to cool down. Now that we have stepper motor based extruders it's possible so I just HAD to create this object using OpenSCAD :) The snap fit handle (needed to keep the lower part flat and printable) was inspired by the printed axis in the "Screwless Cube Gears" by emmett http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10483

If you have a well calibrated printer the handle should snap fit right into the hole in the spintop. 
I printed using skeinforge and so the hole came out a little bit too small. Instead of making the model smaller which would lead to problems for the people whose printers print to spec I filed down the handle a little bit to snap fit it in.
Assemble the 2 pieces and have fun!

After trying several variations of the RostockMAX hot-end fan ducts/shrouds available on Thingiverse I was left unsatisfied. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:43983 came close to what I wanted, but as I apparently have SeeMeCNC's v2 nozzle it didn't fit. I spent a good deal of time learning new surface modeling techniques in ProE so that I could design this duct. It has a very simple mount that grasps the aluminum stand-off in the corner of the stock SeeMeCNC effector and uses a single screw through the unused hole to secure it in place. There shouldn't be any interferences on a stock setup. While it looks quite close to the hot-end, I ran these ducts for nearly 100 hours of printing and noticed no heat-induced deformation of the duct. I found that a single duct improved print performance (I use ABS, but I'm sure it will help PLA as well) satisfactorily, but I printed two because I had two 40mm fans. I wouldn't say it doubled the cooling performance, but it was better. I would imagine that a third would again be helpful, but I would also begin worrying about the additional weight on the effector. As it usually goes, I have even further modified my MAX to use magnetic (ball-joint) arms and these ducts are now desk decorations. The new effector and cooling design is soon to come...

Print both parts. I don't remember my exact print settings, but I think I used 3 perimeters on the mount with 60% infill and 1 perimeter on the duct. Both were printed at 0.2mm layer height with a 0.5mm nozzle. I used M3 screws, but #6 would work just as well (they differ by 0.0015 in). On the duct I ran an M3 plug tap through the four fan mounting holes and an M3 bottoming tap in the duct-to-mount holes on the side to prevent over stressing the plastic during assembly and avoid any cracking or splitting. I would also recommend a very thin piece of neoprene or other light-weight foam rubber as a vibration-absorbing gasket between the fan to be mounted and the duct. Steppers, especially those that are using any form of micro-stepping, are very sensitive to vibrations and if your fans are not well balanced, you might introduce a source of missed steps.

OpenSCAD module/library to simplify the design of rectangular shaped compartment trays.
The tray is defined via an ASCII art method , and combined with sizing parameters, a custom compartmentalized tray is generated.  
Need a lid?  No problem, with the same tray layout parameters and a few extra values to designate a lid, your things will be secured in your tray even when flipped upside down.  The lid will need to be generated separately. 
I have used this to organize some items, and also organize board game components.
See the tray layout instructions attachment/image to understand how to design your custom tray.

OpenSCAD Library Info A bunch of compromises were made to make this work with the Thingiverse Customizer feature. Using this as a library is easier, since the tray layout parameter is passed as an array of strings. All the other parameters are still used, but this may be much easier to use in OpenSCAD, if you are familiar with OpenSCAD.
